message.body: every entity has what's called an event number. when you interact with something like a door, it runs the script event in your current map associated with that number

fragments.text: every entity has what's called an event number. when you interact with something like a door, it runs the script event in your current map associated with that number

message.body: each map has its own script file

fragments.text: each map has its own script file

message.body: the bug allows you to transplant a script file from one map to another

fragments.text: the bug allows you to transplant a script file from one map to another

message.body: but critically, there's often a lot of overlap in event numbers between two different script files

fragments.text: but critically, there's often a lot of overlap in event numbers between two different script files

message.body: and even better: if you try to run an event that doesn't exist, the game will run whatever event would come next

fragments.text: and even better: if you try to run an event that doesn't exist, the game will run whatever event would come next

message.body: it is an ordered list of numbers yeah

message.body: so if you interact with entity 200, but the script only has events 199 and 201, it'll run event 201
